iors.  With their regeneration and massive size, the Tier’dal would no doubt use the Homeless race as a standing army against their enemies.  This thought made Daiunus scowl openly, sending a younger Troll scampering away towards its mother, misunderstanding his disdain as one towards them, when instead it was for them, knowing his people would only use them for their purposes, giving the Homeless no pure cause to fight, such as he would given time.  He looked at the expressions of the Migrants, and saw only one emotion, that of hopelessness.  This did not discourage him however, for he knew, given time, the Homeless Race would soon learn to Hate those who stole their homes and killed their brothers.<br>
<br>
        He would send one of his Disciples down to the gates to hire some of these formidable Creatures as guards for the Grange.  He would pay, house and arm the warriors, as well as giving their families housing somewhere in the old servants’ quarters of the Grange.  Daiunus nodded and smiled to himself, he knew Innoruuk’s new calling would allow for this, for this treatment of non Tier’dal within the walls of Neriak.  He had been told, not by a voice, but by a dream.   He had been standing in the large antechamber of War within the Grange, no table to be seen, and the raised dais removed, leaving the room at one level.  Around him, standing in a circle had been many people, some he recognized and others he didn’t.  Some were Tier’dal, but not all, as was the case in the old days of the Violent Harvest.  To his left was Lyri, the druidess of the Harvest, who had forsaken Tunare to join the cause of Hate; to his right, an Iksar he did not recognize, he believed it to be one of the necromancers of the race.  Others in the circle were new to him as well, a female Barbarian, a shamaness, he knew from experience, although her hair was darker than that of Payle, one of the old members of the Harvest, although lost, Daiunus still felt a devotion to her as well.  He even had thought he had seen one of the foul Frogloks in the court, one of the race that had so recently dispelled the Trolls from their swamp.<br>
<br>
        The one thing he did understand from this vision, was that in the new Court of Hate, there would be no ruling race.  All who were touched by Innoruuk’s Might would be welcome for the Culling as equals to the once Chosen race.  That left many things to be done before he could face the man he betrayed.  The Thresher, for he wished to be called that once more, had betrayed his liege, Khasirath, and knew that a time of reckoning would be coming for the once-leader of the Violent Harvest.  Before Daiunus could lay down his arms and accept the Reaper’s judgement, he had to complete the calling to arms of the Grange.  Only then, would he sit and wait for the Reaper’s judgement, until that time, he would continue to avoid the city guard.<br>
<br>
        The Thresher knew his next step was to recall those he could find, he began setting letters to those who had served Innoruuk in the past.   Zirrix and Tzlar, the brothers who held more sway in Neriak than any two others he could think of;  Taelea and Vladire, both priestesses of great power to Innoruuk’s cause; Xareth and Faeolin, both whom were Dread Overlords within the Grange’s hierarchy; Nospiratus, the mad Prophet, who was known to be lost to Norrath’s world; Vresk, the once Ambassador to Hate from Cabalis; Pravdameer, the Prophet of Innoruuk; Katarinia, a chantress of no small power.  There were so many he would have to try to contact, and he knew most would not answer the call, but he would try.  <br>
<br>
        Daiunus continued drafting letters well into the night, he had remembered so many more since first sitting down to write.  Crieth, Natori, Vkos, Cynr, Sithmar, Safyran, Vinar, all of whom were essential to the growth and stability of the Harvest of old.  Some of whom had places of power within Neriak or the Grange, others who were more loyal than any other he could think of.  Soon, he would have them together, in one room, to speak of the coming glories of the Chosen.  The ones in his dreams would have to reach him another way, for he had no names to go with the faces shown to him by Innoruuk’s power.<br>
<br>
By morning, finished his letters to his closest friends and allies, he began the walk from his War room to his bedchamber.  As he was walking the hallways to his room, he saw down a staircase, four large Trolls being outfitted by Espion, who looked frazzled from trying to outfit the oversized warriors into gear that mostly were made for the comparably diminutive Tier’dal.  He smiled as he continued on towards his much deserved sleep, knowing that everything was going to work out in Innoruuk’s Favor.<br>
<br>
<br>
*** The letter sent to the former members of the Harvest***<br>
<br>
Dear ,<br>
<br>
The culling has returned, Innoruuk's word has reached me, and I am sure you know what I mean by this, for you have no doubt had something of the vision as well.  The Grange has opened, and I dwell inside.  Return to Innoruuk at haste, I await your arrival.<br>
<br>
<br>
Daiunus Darkenvalor<br>
Loyal servant to our Father<br>
