<br>
Her eyes had locked with one individual that she did recognize.   Daiunus, the dark figure that she had met at the Dragon of Hate.  For what seemed to be an eternity, she stared into his eyes.   Before her, his form changed, taking that of Innoruuk, and with a voice that seared painfully into her mind, he whispered, “It’s time.”  <br>
<br>
Before she could blink, before her again stood Daiunus, and the vision was done, leaving the young rogue alone in the vacant room of the inn.  After catching her breath, and restoring her disheveled appearance to something approaching orderly, Cearyn threw a few of her belongings into a travel pack.  With a coin purse visible in her hand, she approached the inkeep.  “I will be leaving today, but I wish to maintain my room here.  6 months of rent, as well as ample compensation to see that it is left untouched.  Soon, a list of those welcome to enter will reach you.  See to it that they are not bothered.”<br>
<br>
She knew the inkeep to be true to his dealings, and to be a man of great discretion.  It was this discretion that earned the man most of his profits, and the reputation for silence that he had earned was his most valuable asset in this business.<br>
<br>
Cearyn set a quick pace back to Neriak.  She knew, from the moment that she had met Daiunus that her fate was somehow to be tied to his.   She knew, when he spoke of the Harvest that her path would be entwined with it.  As soon as the words, “You will know,” left his tongue, she knew.  The dream-vision had only provided her with details for a knowledge that had come to her that day.<br>
<br>
